  "chunk_index": 38,
  "summary": "Simonne, a medium, expresses her fear to Raoul regarding the concept of motherhood, noting that maternal love is a primal force capable of destruction. After Simonne rests, Raoul prepares a room for a séance, with Elise arranging necessary items including a tambourine, a horn, and writing materials. An old servant announces the arrival of Madame Iex, a tall, melancholy woman.\n\nTo manage expectations, Raoul attempts to explain the phenomena scientifically, claiming that \"ghosts\" are actually compressed gases from the medium's own body and warning that touching them could kill the medium. Despite Raoul's skepticism, Madame Iex is eager to see her deceased daughter, Emily. Simonne joins them, appearing pale and exhausted, but insists on proceeding with the séance.\n\nTo ensure there is no conspiracy, Madame Iex produces a rope from her handbag and methodically ties Raoul to a chair. She then locks the hallway door and removes the key. As the séance begins, Simonne’s breathing becomes heavy and transitions into a moan. Suddenly, cymbals and bells sound, and a horn is thrown to the ground. A mist of vapor escapes Simonne's mouth and condenses into the figure of a small child. Madame Iex reacts with intense emotion as the figure of Emily appears, calling out \"Mommy!\" and stepping through the curtain toward her. Raoul watches in amazement, perceiving the manifestation as a real, living child.",
